<PubmedArticle><MedlineCitation Status="MEDLINE" Owner="NLM" IndexingMethod="Manual"><PMID Version="1">25827059</PMID><DateCompleted><Year>2016</Year><Month>05</Month><Day>20</Day></DateCompleted><DateRevised><Year>2016</Year><Month>09</Month><Day>11</Day></DateRevised><Article PubModel="Print-Electronic"><Journal><ISSN IssnType="Electronic">1466-447X</ISSN><JournalIssue CitedMedium="Internet"><Volume>33</Volume><Issue>19</Issue><PubDate><Year>2015</Year></PubDate></JournalIssue><Title>Journal of sports sciences</Title><ISOAbbreviation>J Sports Sci</ISOAbbreviation></Journal><ArticleTitle>Effects of sodium phosphate and caffeine loading on repeated-sprint ability.</ArticleTitle><Pagination><StartPage>1971</StartPage><EndPage>1979</EndPage><MedlinePgn>1971-9</MedlinePgn></Pagination><ELocationID EIdType="doi" ValidYN="Y">10.1080/02640414.2015.1025235</ELocationID><Abstract><AbstractText>The effects of sodium phosphate and caffeine supplementation were assessed on repeated-sprint ability. Using a randomised, double-blind, Latin-square design, 12 female, team-sport players participated in four trials: (1) sodium phosphate and caffeine, (2) sodium phosphate and placebo (for caffeine), (3) caffeine and placebo (for sodium phosphate) and (4) placebo (for sodium phosphate and caffeine), with ~21&#xa0;days separating each trial. After each trial, participants performed a simulated team-game circuit (4&#xa0;&#xd7;&#xa0;15&#xa0;min quarters) with 6&#xa0;&#xd7;&#xa0;20-m repeated-sprints performed once before (Set 1), at half-time (Set 2), and after end (Set 3). Total sprint times were faster after sodium phosphate and caffeine supplementation compared with placebo (Set 1: P&#xa0;=&#xa0;0.003; Set 2: d&#xa0;=&#xa0;-0.51; Set 3: P&#xa0;&lt;&#xa0;0.001; overall: P&#xa0;=&#xa0;0.020), caffeine (Set 3: P&#xa0;=&#xa0;0.004; overall: P&#xa0;=&#xa0;0.033) and sodium phosphate (Set 3: d&#xa0;=&#xa0;-0.67). Furthermore, total sprint times were faster after sodium phosphate supplementation compared with placebo (Set 1: d&#xa0;=&#xa0;-0.52; Set 3: d&#xa0;=&#xa0;-0.58). Best sprint results were faster after sodium phosphate and caffeine supplementation compared with placebo (Set 3: P&#xa0;=&#xa0;0.007, d&#xa0;=&#xa0;-0.90) and caffeine (Set 3: P&#xa0;=&#xa0;0.024, d&#xa0;=&#xa0;-0.73). Best sprint times were also faster after sodium phosphate supplementation compared with placebo (d&#xa0;=&#xa0;-0.54 to -0.61 for all sets). Sodium phosphate and combined sodium phosphate and caffeine loading improved repeated-sprint ability.</AbstractText></Abstract><AuthorList CompleteYN="Y"><Author ValidYN="Y"><LastName>Buck</LastName><ForeName>Christopher</ForeName><Initials>C</Initials><AffiliationInfo><Affiliation>a The University of Western Australia , School of Sport Science, Exercise and Health , Perth , Australia.</Affiliation></AffiliationInfo></Author><Author ValidYN="Y"><LastName>Guelfi</LastName><ForeName>Kym</ForeName><Initials>K</Initials><AffiliationInfo><Affiliation>a The University of Western Australia , School of Sport Science, Exercise and Health , Perth , Australia.</Affiliation></AffiliationInfo></Author><Author ValidYN="Y"><LastName>Dawson</LastName><ForeName>Brian</ForeName><Initials>B</Initials><AffiliationInfo><Affiliation>a The University of Western Australia , School of Sport Science, Exercise and Health , Perth , Australia.</Affiliation></AffiliationInfo></Author><Author ValidYN="Y"><LastName>McNaughton</LastName><ForeName>Lars</ForeName><Initials>L</Initials><AffiliationInfo><Affiliation>b Edge Hill University , Sport and Physical activity , Lancashire , UK.</Affiliation></AffiliationInfo></Author><Author ValidYN="Y"><LastName>Wallman</LastName><ForeName>Karen</ForeName><Initials>K</Initials><AffiliationInfo><Affiliation>a The University of Western Australia , School of Sport Science, Exercise and Health , Perth , Australia.</Affiliation></AffiliationInfo></Author></AuthorList><Language>eng</Language><PublicationTypeList><PublicationType